<article>
    <h1>Re&#xAD;duce your chances of be&#xAD;ing bit&#xAD;ten</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200727/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-27"><time>2020-07-27</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE MIND &amp; BODY</span>
        - <span role="byline">Am&#xAD;rita Kaur</span>
    </section>

    <p>Dengue fever is wide­spread in Sin­ga­pore and in South-east Asia. This is closely tied to the preva­lence of the Aedes mos­quito, the trans­mit­ter of the in­fec­tion.</p>
    <p>Dr Leong Hoe Nam, an in­fec­tious dis­ease spe­cial­ist at Mount El­iz­a­beth Novena Hospi­tal, gives tips to pre­vent one­self from be­ing in­fected.</p>
    <p>1. EX­POSE AS LIT­TLE SKIN AS POS­SI­BLE</p>
    <p>The best pro­tec­tion is to avoid get­ting bit­ten by mos­qui­toes. The chances of be­ing bit­ten are sig­nif­i­cantly re­duced if you ex­pose as lit­tle skin as pos­si­ble. Wear long pants, a long-sleeved shirt and socks when you are in an area with mos­qui­toes.</p>
    <p>2. USE MOS­QUITO RE­PEL­LENT</p>
    <p>Use a mos­quito re­pel­lent with at least 10 per cent di­ethyl­tolu­amide (Deet), a sub­stance that re­pels bit­ing pests. A higher con­cen­tra­tion of Deet is nec­es­sary for longer lengths of ex­po­sure, but avoid us­ing it on young chil­dren.</p>
    <p>Also, avoid wear­ing heav­ily scented soaps and per­fumes as th­ese are known to at­tract mos­qui­toes.</p>
    <p>3. IN­STALL STRUC­TURAL BAR­RI­ERS</p>
    <p>In­stall struc­tural bar­ri­ers such as win­dow screens or in­sec­ti­cide-treated net­ting at home. Nets that have been treated with in­sec­ti­cide not only kill mos­qui­toes and other in­sects, but are also a phys­i­cal bar­rier that pre­vents them from en­ter­ing the room.</p>
    <p>4. ELIM­I­NATE BREED­ING GROUNDS</p>
    <p>Aedes mos­qui­toes pre­fer to breed in clean, stag­nant wa­ter, so be sure to elim­i­nate any pos­si­ble breed­ing lo­ca­tions. This in­cludes buck­ets, wa­ter­ing cans and re­cep­ta­cles.</p>
    <p>Make it a habit of reg­u­larly clean­ing and scrub­bing plant pots to re­move mos­quito eggs. Loosen soil from pot­ted plants to pre­vent pud­dles from form­ing on the sur­face of hard soil.</p>
    <p>5. VAC­CI­NA­TION</p>
    <p>The dengue vac­cine Deng­vaxia was ap­proved by the Health Sciences Au­thor­ity in Oc­to­ber 2016 for use in peo­ple aged be­tween 12 and 45. Those who wish to be vac­ci­nated should first con­sult a doc­tor.</p>


